Section 1:
1 L.D. 405
2 Date: (Filing No. H- )
3 CRIMINAL JUSTICE AND PUBLIC SAFETY
5 STATE OF MAINE
6 HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 259, L.D. 405, “An Act to Define
10 "Solitary Confinement" for the Laws Governing Jails and Correctional Facilities”
11 Amend the bill by striking out the title and substituting the following:
12 'An Act to Remove the Terms "Solitary Confinement" and "Confinement" from the
13 Laws Governing Corrections'
14 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the enacting clause and inserting the
15 following:
16 'Sec. 1. 34-A MRSA §3032, sub-§3, ¶D, as amended by PL 1989, c. 127, §6, is
17 further amended to read:
18 D. When segregation exceeds 24 hours, the chief administrative officer of the
19 correctional facility shall cause the facility's physician or a member of the facility's
20 medical staff to visit the person immediately and, at least once in each succeeding 24-
21 hour period of confinement segregation, to examine the person's state of health. When
22 no physician or medical staff member is available within the facility to visit as required
23 by this paragraph, a staff person who has received in-service training appropriate for
24 the duties required by this section from a licensed health professional shall visit in lieu
25 of the visit by the physician or medical staff member the person in confinement
26 segregation. The staff person making the visit shall immediately contact the physician
27 or medical staff member on call if there is reasonable cause to believe the action is
28 necessary.
29 (1) The chief administrative officer shall give full consideration to
30 recommendations of the physician or medical staff member as to the person's
31 dietary needs and the conditions of the person's confinement segregation required
32 to maintain that person's health.
33 (2) If the recommendations of the physician or medical staff member regarding a
34 person's dietary or other health needs while in segregation are not carried out, the
35 chief administrative officer shall immediately convey the reasons and
Page 1 - 132LR1006(03)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 259, L.D. 405
316 circumstances for this decision to the commissioner for review and final
327 disposition.
3 Sec. 2. 34-A MRSA §3032, sub-§3, ¶E, as enacted by PL 1983, c. 459, §6, is
4 amended to read:
5 E. If a person is held in segregation or solitary confinement for more than 5 days, the
6 chief administrative officer shall send a report of the confinement segregation to the
7 commissioner, giving the reasons for the confinement segregation.'
8 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
9 number to read consecutively.
10 SUMMARY
1111 This amendment, which is the minority report of the committee, replaces the bill and
1122 changes the title. The amendment removes certain references to solitary confinement and
1133 confinement currently in statute and replaces the references with the term segregation.
Page 2 - 132LR1006(03)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
